<subSubSection id="6E8C6532290B3272FF2E2C59FDE5D825" pageId="1" pageNumber="251" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="262936B9290B3272FF2E2C59FDE5D825" blockId="1.[151,1437,1292,1930]" pageId="1" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="14E2EAAB290B3272FF2E2C59FEBFD879" bold="true" box="[199,315,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="251">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished from other species by the very short and stout aedeagus with pair of furcate processes arising apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6E8C6532290B3272FF2E2C11FE06D8ED" pageId="1" pageNumber="251" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="262936B9290B3272FF2E2C11FE06D8ED" blockId="1.[151,1437,1292,1930]" pageId="1" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="14E2EAAB290B3272FF2E2C11FECAD801" bold="true" box="[199,334,1868,1894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="251">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Latin word 
<taxonomicName id="E1964D3A290B3272FC972C10FC57D801" authorityName="Gou &amp; Xing" authorityYear="2022" box="[894,979,1869,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Longicornus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="251" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grossus">
<emphasis id="14E2EAAB290B3272FC972C10FC57D801" box="[894,979,1869,1894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="251">grossus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, indicating the short and robust aedeagal shaft in ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
